#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:5
msgid ""
"In Toonz it is possible to draw Vector levels (PLI format), Toonz "
"raster levels (TLV format) and standard raster levels (TIF format) "
"directly in the work area. Drawing tools can also be used for touch-up in"
" cleaned up drawings, and any loaded raster images."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:10
msgid "Drawing In Toonz"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:11
msgid ""
"To draw an animation level, first you have to define its type, Toonz "
"vector, Smart Raster or raster, and its settings like its name, the "
"number of frames it is made of and the way its drawings are numbered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:13
msgid ""
"Vector levels are defined by drawing vector strokes; vectors and "
"areas defined by vectors can be painted by using the styles available in "
"the level palette. Vector levels have unlimited size and "
"resolution, as they are vector-based. They are saved as PLI files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:15
msgid ""
"Starting from Toonz Harlequin 6.4 ML, vector levels (PLI files) created "
"with Toonz are not compatible with previous versions of the software."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:17
msgid ""
"Smart Raster levels are defined by drawing bitmap lines; lines and areas "
"defined by lines can be painted by using the styles available in the "
"level palette. Smart Raster levels have a limited size and resolution, "
"defined when they are created. They are saved as TLV files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:19
msgid ""
"Raster levels are defined by drawing bitmap lines using the styles "
"available in the raster drawing palette that is shared by all of the "
"raster levels belonging to a specific project (see  :ref:`Project Default"
" Folders <project_default_folders>`  ). Raster levels have a limited size"
" and resolution, defined when they are created. They are saved as "
"sequences of TIF files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:21
msgid ""
"When an animation level is defined, you can select any of its frame in "
"the xsheet or in the level strip, and start drawing in the work area. You"
" can do this both when you want to create a drawing from scratch, and "
"when you want to edit a previously made drawing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/drawing_animation_levels.rst:23
msgid ""
"When selected in the xsheet, the work area displays the whole scene "
"content at the current frame; when selected in the level strip, the work "
"area displays the selected frame of the current animation level only, to "
"let you work more easily on it."
msgstr ""

